WEBVTT

02:54.348 --> 02:56.524
[ Sighs ]

03:02.834 --> 03:04.271
Man: Iris!

03:04.314 --> 03:06.142
Iris, w-wait for me!

03:06.186 --> 03:09.450
Just keep tight hold of me,
and it'll be all right!

03:09.493 --> 03:10.581
You won't keep still!

03:10.625 --> 03:11.843
I can'tkeep still!

03:11.887 --> 03:13.236
I can't catch up
with you!

03:13.280 --> 03:14.281
Speed up!

03:14.324 --> 03:15.760
[ Laughing ] Oh!

03:15.804 --> 03:17.327
[ Laughing ] Whoo!

03:17.371 --> 03:20.330
[ Church bells ringing ]

03:37.565 --> 03:39.871
Iris, you've got bicycle oil
on your ankle.

03:39.915 --> 03:43.223
I don't care, John.
Oh.

03:43.266 --> 03:44.920
Woman: Those of you,
our guests,

03:44.963 --> 03:47.705
on whose magnificent
generosity we depend --

03:47.749 --> 03:50.142
we really are most
frightfully grateful --

03:50.186 --> 03:51.666
will need no introduction

03:51.709 --> 03:55.583
to one of our most
distinguished graduates

03:55.626 --> 03:58.194
and an honorary fellow,
Dame Iris Murdoch.

03:58.238 --> 04:01.632
She's a noted philosopher

04:01.676 --> 04:04.592
as well as author
of some 26 novels,

04:04.635 --> 04:07.290
and we are honored
to have her with us today,

04:07.334 --> 04:11.338
as well as the distinguished
Wharton professor of literature,

04:11.381 --> 04:15.385
who has the great good fortune
of being married to her.

04:15.429 --> 04:20.303
I need to say no more about her
for good wine needs no bush.

04:20.346 --> 04:22.436
But she will not
mind comparison

04:22.479 --> 04:24.786
with, say, a really fine
vintage Claret.

04:24.829 --> 04:27.092
[ Laughter ]

04:27.136 --> 04:29.443
Dame Iris will speak to you

04:29.486 --> 04:33.403
about the importance
of education.

04:46.198 --> 04:48.462
Education doesn't
make you happy,

04:48.505 --> 04:52.030
and nor does freedom.

04:52.074 --> 04:55.207
We don't become happy just
because we're free, if we are,

04:55.251 --> 04:59.951
or because we've been educated,
if we have,

04:59.995 --> 05:03.128
but because education
may be the means

05:03.172 --> 05:05.305
by which we realize
we are happy.

05:05.348 --> 05:09.091
It opens our eyes,
our ears...

05:09.134 --> 05:11.441
tells us where delights
are lurking...

05:11.485 --> 05:15.010
convinces us that there
is only one freedom

05:15.053 --> 05:19.667
of any importance whatsoever --
that of the mind --

05:19.710 --> 05:21.669
and gives us the assurance,

05:21.712 --> 05:24.541
the confidence,
to walk the path our mind --

05:24.585 --> 05:28.110
our educated mind -- offers.

05:31.243 --> 05:34.377
♪ I shall tell him
all my love ♪

05:34.421 --> 05:38.250
♪ All my soul's adoration

05:38.294 --> 05:43.255
♪ And I think he will hear me

05:43.299 --> 05:48.130
♪ And will not say me nay

05:48.173 --> 05:51.394
♪ It is this
that gives my soul ♪

05:51.438 --> 05:56.878
♪ All its joyous elation

05:56.921 --> 06:02.492
♪ As I hear
the sweet lark sing ♪

06:02.536 --> 06:07.497
♪ In the clear air
of the day ♪

06:07.541 --> 06:09.064
Young Iris: Yes, of course,
there's something fishy

06:09.107 --> 06:12.154
about describing
people's feelings.

06:12.197 --> 06:13.895
You try hard to be accurate,
but as soon as you

06:13.938 --> 06:16.419
start to define such and such a
feeling, language lets you down.

06:16.463 --> 06:18.378
It's really a machine
for making falsehoods.

06:18.421 --> 06:21.250
When we really speak the truth,
words are insufficient.

06:21.293 --> 06:25.167
Almost everything except
things like "pass the gravy"

06:25.210 --> 06:26.516
is a lie of a sort.

06:26.560 --> 06:28.692
And that being the case,
I shall shut up.

06:28.736 --> 06:30.346
[ Laughter ]

06:30.390 --> 06:31.782
Oh, and...pass the gravy.

06:31.826 --> 06:32.696
[ Laughter ]

06:37.048 --> 06:39.311
But love,
which is unsatisfying...

06:39.355 --> 06:41.879
and real love -- extreme
love -- once it's recognized --

06:41.923 --> 06:44.273
has the stamp
of the indubitable --

06:44.316 --> 06:47.798
Ah, John. I may call
you John, mayn't I?
Meet Miss Murdoch.

06:47.842 --> 06:49.452
Iris, my dear, John Bayley,
one of the more promising

06:49.496 --> 06:51.454
young lecturers
in the English school.

06:51.498 --> 06:53.761
Though I called him out
over Old-English grammar,

06:53.804 --> 06:55.545
his weaker side, I fear,

06:55.589 --> 06:59.375
a minor question of
Anglo-Saxon syntax.

07:01.116 --> 07:04.989
[ Coughing ]
Wine.

07:05.033 --> 07:08.253
I mean, went down
the wrong way.

07:08.297 --> 07:09.646
Yes, I like that.

07:09.690 --> 07:11.996
There is a right way down,
of course.

07:12.040 --> 07:16.479
Amazing how most of us find it
without even thinking about it.

07:16.523 --> 07:18.655
Oh, I-I r-rarely think.

07:18.699 --> 07:20.614
If you think about it,
you'll never find it.

07:20.657 --> 07:24.139
Best thing to do is hang on
and trust the body. I do.

07:24.182 --> 07:25.880
Iris: Human beings
love each other --

07:25.923 --> 07:30.275
in sex, in friendship,
and when they're in love.

07:30.319 --> 07:35.063
And they cherish
other beings --

07:35.106 --> 07:40.503
humans, animals, plants,
even stones.

07:40.547 --> 07:44.159
The quest for happiness
and the promotion of happiness

07:44.202 --> 07:45.465
is in all of this

07:45.508 --> 07:47.597
and the power
of our imagination.

07:47.641 --> 07:51.296
I'm writing a n-novel.

07:51.340 --> 07:54.212
I don't suppose you have
the time or the inclination

07:54.256 --> 07:56.127
to even r-r-read
a n-novel.

07:56.171 --> 07:58.739
I've written one.
It's going to be published.

07:58.782 --> 07:59.957
And I'm writing another.

08:00.001 --> 08:02.220
Oh. C-C-Can I --
can I read it?

08:02.264 --> 08:06.790
No one has read it.
None of my friends.

08:06.834 --> 08:08.792
What's it about?

08:08.836 --> 08:10.011
About?

08:10.054 --> 08:12.187
It has something
for everyone.

08:12.230 --> 08:13.971
A b-bit like Shakespeare?

08:14.015 --> 08:19.020
Perhaps, yes.
Please don't talk
to anyone about it.

08:19.063 --> 08:20.238
N-N-N-No.

08:20.282 --> 08:22.153
Of c-course not.

08:22.197 --> 08:23.894
I-I-I w-won't
t-tell a soul.

08:30.814 --> 08:33.643
Iris:
Every human soul has seen,

08:33.687 --> 08:36.558
perhaps even before
their birth,

08:36.602 --> 08:42.565
pure forms such as justice,
temperance, beauty,

08:42.609 --> 08:44.654
and all the great
moral qualities

08:44.698 --> 08:46.308
which we hold in honor.

08:46.351 --> 08:48.615
We are moved towards
what is good

08:48.658 --> 08:51.835
by the faint memory
of these forms,

08:51.879 --> 08:55.970
simple and calm and blessed,

08:56.013 --> 09:00.148
which we saw once
in a pure, clear light

09:00.191 --> 09:03.020
being pure ourselves.

09:03.064 --> 09:06.589
[ Indistinct talking
on P.A. system ]

09:06.633 --> 09:08.112
Whole grain.

09:08.156 --> 09:10.593
Do we have whole grain
or something other?

09:10.637 --> 09:13.683
What is "whole"?

09:13.727 --> 09:15.729
Is it something in itself
or does it have parts?

09:15.772 --> 09:17.382
Oh, spaghetti.

09:17.426 --> 09:18.906
If you have a whole,
you have a whole.

09:18.949 --> 09:20.690
Ooh, sausages.
You and me is a whole.

09:20.734 --> 09:22.953
If you toddle off, there's a
hole in the whole, or if I do.

09:22.997 --> 09:25.260
But a whole can't be broken.
It just forms another whole.

09:25.303 --> 09:27.262
Baked beans.
Baked beans!

09:27.305 --> 09:29.743
Do you want premium points?

09:29.786 --> 09:32.267
Do we deserve them?

09:32.310 --> 09:33.964
Do you want bags?

09:34.008 --> 09:35.575
Bags, yes. You know,
it's all around us --

09:35.618 --> 09:36.837
People like you
and me talking nonsense.

09:36.880 --> 09:39.622
I know. I know.

09:39.666 --> 09:40.928
Bag for life?

09:40.971 --> 09:41.929
For life?

09:41.972 --> 09:43.408
That's what it says.

09:43.452 --> 09:44.845
We have to ask --
give you the choice.

09:44.888 --> 09:48.326
Ooh, rather.

09:48.370 --> 09:50.415
You just have to listen --
That's the job.

09:50.459 --> 09:52.635
You call it a job, but it's
like music, what you do.

09:52.679 --> 09:54.768
You live with the angels,
speak their language --

09:54.811 --> 09:58.380
the music of the spheres.

09:58.423 --> 10:02.123
Nowadays, the only language
anyone really understands
is pictures.

10:02.166 --> 10:05.735
Paint the picture.

10:05.779 --> 10:10.305
[ Laughing ] See,
now I'm bagged for life.

10:10.348 --> 10:12.612
Love's the only language
everyone understands.

10:12.655 --> 10:14.135
Ooh, love, yes.

10:14.178 --> 10:18.356
I can read it,
but I can't speak it.

10:18.400 --> 10:23.100
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

10:23.144 --> 10:26.060
Mmm! Ooh.

10:26.103 --> 10:28.105
[ Mumbling ] My coat's
caught on your chair.

10:28.149 --> 10:31.456
[ Coat pulls ]
Mnh!

10:37.462 --> 10:40.291
And the captain said
of the two weevils

10:40.335 --> 10:41.641
who dropped out
of a biscuit,

10:41.684 --> 10:43.381
"Which would you
rather have, Mr. Smith?"

10:43.425 --> 10:45.906
"The bigger one, sir." "Wrong, Mr. Smith, wrong.

10:45.949 --> 10:48.212
"In the Navy,
you should always choose

10:48.256 --> 10:50.606
the lesser of
the two 'weevils.'"
[ evils ]

10:50.650 --> 10:52.260
Patrick O'Brian --
"Between two evils,

10:52.303 --> 10:54.349
always choose the one
you haven't tried before."

10:54.392 --> 10:56.960
Mae West -- "Oh, my vest! I tore
my vest again this morning."

10:57.004 --> 10:58.309
You must get
some new vests.

10:58.353 --> 11:01.138
Jolly good.

11:01.182 --> 11:04.402
You must get
some new vests.

11:04.446 --> 11:07.667
I just said that.

11:07.710 --> 11:11.148
You're always saying that --
That you just said something.
Me too.

11:11.192 --> 11:13.237
Good job. You reminded me
I had two lectures today.

11:13.281 --> 11:15.022
You remembered.

11:15.065 --> 11:16.893
No, but I remembered to
apologize for the one I forgot.

11:16.937 --> 11:18.547
They were very sweet
about it.

11:18.590 --> 11:22.116
Glad not to have to listen
to you, I expect.

11:22.159 --> 11:26.337
Oh, I'm sure.
They'd have been delighted
to have listened to you.

11:26.381 --> 11:28.731
I always have been.

11:28.775 --> 11:31.081
[ Thunder rumbles ]

11:39.263 --> 11:40.221
Iris.

11:40.264 --> 11:43.180
John. Oh!

11:43.224 --> 11:46.140
Thank you.
Keep the change.

11:46.183 --> 11:47.576
Janet! Janet!

11:47.619 --> 11:49.143
Oh, my God, Iris!

11:49.186 --> 11:50.274
Am I late?

11:50.318 --> 11:52.320
Don't be silly.

11:52.363 --> 11:57.760
Oh, no, it's the hokeycokey.
Everything'll be over.

11:57.804 --> 12:00.415
John, wait.Oh, dear.

12:00.458 --> 12:03.548
[ Jazz music plays ]Stupid!

12:20.087 --> 12:23.090
Oops. Sorry.

12:23.133 --> 12:25.962
Cha-cha-cha.

12:26.006 --> 12:27.094
Cha-cha-cha!

12:27.137 --> 12:28.182
Cha-cha-cha.

12:28.225 --> 12:31.446
Ch-- ooh!

12:31.489 --> 12:34.057
Cha-cha-cha.

12:37.365 --> 12:39.497
Thank you!
You too!

12:42.283 --> 12:45.416
That was my husband.

12:45.460 --> 12:47.592
Cha-cha-cha.

12:50.465 --> 12:51.988
Are you with Iris?

12:52.032 --> 12:54.382
H-H-Hoping so.

12:54.425 --> 12:56.645
You know, we have --I-I thought we had.

12:56.688 --> 12:58.647
Nearly met.A-Are you a friend of Iris?

12:58.690 --> 13:00.867
Yes.

13:00.910 --> 13:02.390
She seems
to have a lot of --

13:02.433 --> 13:03.870
♪ Do do do-do do do

13:03.913 --> 13:08.831
[ Laughter ]

13:08.875 --> 13:11.007
Janet Stone, John Bayley.

13:11.051 --> 13:12.661
How do you do?

13:12.704 --> 13:14.184
H-How do you do?

13:14.228 --> 13:15.272
Shall we?

13:15.316 --> 13:17.013
What are your rooms like?

13:17.057 --> 13:18.972
A-Adequate, thank you.

13:19.015 --> 13:21.017
I'd like to see them.
Oh.

13:21.061 --> 13:22.845
[ Indistinct conversations ]

13:22.889 --> 13:26.414
Do you -- do you have
a lot of friends?

13:26.457 --> 13:27.894
Is a list of my friends
necessary?

13:27.937 --> 13:29.852
I-I just wondered
if you had many.

13:29.896 --> 13:32.246
There aren't many people that
one wants to know one. Do you --

13:32.289 --> 13:34.422
Whoop!
Ahhhhhh!

13:34.465 --> 13:35.858
Iris!

13:35.902 --> 13:39.383
[ Laughing ]

13:44.519 --> 13:45.868
Y-You might fall.

13:45.912 --> 13:47.565
W-Would you like some
more c-champagne?

13:47.609 --> 13:48.958
That would be nice.

13:49.002 --> 13:50.438
I-I've had some
s-since Christmas.

13:50.481 --> 13:52.701
It does keep, doesn't it?

14:00.665 --> 14:03.668
I-I s-s-shouldn't
be doing this.

14:03.712 --> 14:05.888
What? H-having women
in my r-room.

14:05.932 --> 14:07.759
It's --
it's not p-permitted.

14:07.803 --> 14:10.588
I wouldn't say
you "had me" exactly.

14:10.632 --> 14:12.808
[ Chuckles ]

14:12.852 --> 14:16.638
Have you danced before?

14:16.681 --> 14:19.075
It was a-all right,
wasn't it?

14:19.119 --> 14:20.511
Oh, I think so.

14:20.555 --> 14:22.949
I-It b-b-broke the ice,
so to speak.

14:22.992 --> 14:26.343
Ice.
What?

14:26.387 --> 14:28.650
Oh! Oh, it'll do.

14:28.693 --> 14:31.348
Aren't you particular
about words at your college?

14:31.392 --> 14:33.568
I-I-I'm only here on
a s-s-sufferance, really,

14:33.611 --> 14:36.092
as a-a tutor and guide.

14:36.136 --> 14:41.097
I-I get all the Americans
and Frenchmen to m-mother.

14:41.141 --> 14:43.970
You love words,
don't you?

14:44.013 --> 14:46.059
If one doesn't have words,
how does one think?

14:48.061 --> 14:50.541
S-Shall I do that?

14:50.585 --> 14:54.937
W-What -- what is your
n-n-n-novel about?

14:54.981 --> 14:56.808
About?

14:56.852 --> 15:01.248
How to be free.
How to be good.

15:01.291 --> 15:03.076
[ Cork pops ]
Ooh!

15:03.119 --> 15:06.253
And how to love.

15:06.296 --> 15:10.126
Well, that's all --
a-all there is, I'd say.

15:10.170 --> 15:12.999
Well, l-language is all
v-very well, you know,

15:13.042 --> 15:16.393
but it's not the only way of
understanding each other.

15:16.437 --> 15:18.395
There's --
t-there's sight and --

15:18.439 --> 15:22.660
and smell and -- and --
a-and touch, of course.

15:27.317 --> 15:29.276
I-I l-love your nose.

15:29.319 --> 15:32.496
It's snub.

15:41.244 --> 15:43.725
Snubby.

15:43.768 --> 15:46.728
S-snubby, snubby.

15:46.771 --> 15:49.557
Snubby, snubby, snubby.

16:11.144 --> 16:15.191
L-Let me do that to you.
Take off your jacket.

16:38.084 --> 16:41.565
I-If we were, a-as it were,
m-married,

16:41.609 --> 16:44.481
w-we could d-do this
all the time...perhaps.

16:46.657 --> 16:48.790
We should be doing it
nearly all the time.

16:48.833 --> 16:50.574
Yes, but i-if...

16:57.277 --> 16:58.930
Thank you.

17:19.864 --> 17:22.519
[ Fox yelps ]

17:30.919 --> 17:32.964
Look.

17:36.751 --> 17:39.058
Ah!

17:39.101 --> 17:43.410
[ Breathing heavily ]

17:43.453 --> 17:45.847
You stopped
with your working.

17:45.890 --> 17:49.111
Yes, well, I don't mind.

17:49.155 --> 17:51.418
How's it coming along?

17:51.461 --> 17:55.987
It's harder to write than
all the others -- much.
Have you noticed?

17:56.031 --> 18:01.993
Just that you've seemed...
puzzled every now and again.

18:02.037 --> 18:05.040
That's it, yes.

18:05.084 --> 18:06.215
Puzzled.

18:08.478 --> 18:10.915
Puzz -- pu --

18:10.959 --> 18:14.310
Puzzled.
It's a funny word.

18:14.354 --> 18:18.967
All words are like that when
you take them by surprise,
aren't they?

18:19.010 --> 18:22.666
Have you got a title?

18:22.710 --> 18:26.148
A lot of trees
seem near.

18:26.192 --> 18:28.019
[ Cat snarls,
fox yelps ]

18:32.198 --> 18:34.113
We must stop it.

18:34.156 --> 18:35.723
What to do?
What to do?

18:35.766 --> 18:39.509
The window, John.
The window!
We must stop it!

18:39.553 --> 18:41.163
No, see?

18:41.207 --> 18:42.817
It's gone.

18:50.781 --> 18:53.262
We all worry about going mad,
don't we?

18:53.306 --> 18:58.049
How would we know --

18:58.093 --> 19:00.443
those of us who live
in our minds anyway?

19:03.925 --> 19:06.971
Other people would tell us.

19:07.015 --> 19:09.104
Would they, John?

19:09.148 --> 19:13.282
[ "I Don't Want to Set the World
on Fire" by the Inkspots plays ]

19:13.326 --> 19:16.024
[ Bicycle bell rings ]Sorry.

19:16.067 --> 19:21.247
♪ I don't want to set
the world on fire ♪

19:24.554 --> 19:25.947
John Bayley.

19:25.990 --> 19:29.168
♪ I just want to start

19:29.211 --> 19:32.214
♪ A flame in your heart

19:35.826 --> 19:38.655
♪ In my heart

19:38.699 --> 19:43.094
♪ I have but one desire...

19:45.271 --> 19:46.663
I haven't seen her
for ages.

19:46.707 --> 19:49.840
Oh, j-jolly good.
Nice.

19:49.884 --> 19:51.451
Takes all sorts.

19:51.494 --> 19:53.322
N-Not that I --

19:53.366 --> 19:55.455
We're all -- we're all
m-men at St. Anthony's.

19:55.498 --> 19:58.109
Do -- do you like women?

19:58.153 --> 20:01.156
I-I mean, do --
do w-w-women like you?

20:01.200 --> 20:03.985
You mean lesbians?

20:04.028 --> 20:05.247
Yes.

20:05.291 --> 20:07.206
Would it bother you
if they did?

20:07.249 --> 20:08.468
Oh, the s-same thing
happens with me --

20:08.511 --> 20:09.686
with h-h-homosexuals,
I mean.

20:09.730 --> 20:10.774
And do you
go to bed with them?

20:10.818 --> 20:13.560
Lord, no.

20:13.603 --> 20:18.565
At the college,
somebody once said to me,

20:18.608 --> 20:20.523
"Old-fashioned lesbians
of the very highest type."

20:20.567 --> 20:22.351
[ Laughing ]

20:22.395 --> 20:25.789
And -- and d-do --
do you go to bed with them?

20:29.532 --> 20:32.622
[ Typewriter clicking ]

21:02.957 --> 21:04.219
[ Sighs ]

21:06.265 --> 21:09.268
Tsk. Wh--

21:13.663 --> 21:16.100
[ Sighs deeply ]

21:27.895 --> 21:30.332
[ Dog barking in distance ]

21:46.696 --> 21:49.612
[ Indistinct drunken singing ]

23:05.775 --> 23:07.647
Dame Iris.

23:07.690 --> 23:09.997
It's this way.

23:10.040 --> 23:12.956
Woman: She's written philosophy
and plays and poetry,

23:13.000 --> 23:17.265
but her novels are her
lasting literary legacy.

23:17.308 --> 23:20.442
Iris Murdoch is acknowledged
as the foremost English novelist

23:20.486 --> 23:21.878
of her generation.

23:21.922 --> 23:24.620
A little excessive,
don't you think?

23:24.664 --> 23:30.278
What do you reckon?
Shall I take that again?

23:30.321 --> 23:32.149
Her novels embrace
the subjects of freedom

23:32.193 --> 23:35.239
and what it means to be good.

23:35.283 --> 23:36.980
Dame Iris?

23:37.024 --> 23:39.548
...in the successes
and failures of love.

23:39.592 --> 23:42.812
She's written philosophy
and plays and poetry,

23:42.856 --> 23:44.945
but her novels are her
lasting literary legacy.

23:44.988 --> 23:47.338
Young Iris:
People, of course,
are very secretive.

23:47.382 --> 23:52.561
And, for many reasons, want to
appear what we call ordinary.

23:52.605 --> 23:57.827
Everybody has thoughts
they want to conceal...

23:57.871 --> 24:02.919
perhaps even quite simple
aspects of their lives.

24:02.963 --> 24:05.792
People have obsessions
and fears and passions

24:05.835 --> 24:08.272
which they don't admit to.

24:08.316 --> 24:14.017
I think any character is
interesting and has extremes.

24:14.061 --> 24:16.498
It's the novelist's privilege

24:16.542 --> 24:20.894
to see how odd everyone is.

24:20.937 --> 24:24.288
Woman: In your novels,
you yourself are very exact

24:24.332 --> 24:26.116
in your use of language.

24:26.160 --> 24:28.467
But in general terms,
do you think the language

24:28.510 --> 24:29.685
is becoming debased?

24:29.729 --> 24:32.601
Reading and writing

24:32.645 --> 24:37.432
and the preservation
of language and its forms

24:37.476 --> 24:42.350
and the kind of eloquence
and the kind of beauty

24:42.393 --> 24:44.831
that language is capable of

24:44.874 --> 24:48.269
is something terribly
important to human beings

24:48.312 --> 24:53.404
because...this is connected
to thought.

24:53.448 --> 24:55.711
If children are not taught...

25:06.896 --> 25:09.246
W-What did you say?
D-Did you ask --

25:09.290 --> 25:11.161
I was asking about
the importance of language.

25:37.013 --> 25:38.406
Iris: John!

25:38.449 --> 25:40.713
[ Door opens ]
John!

25:40.756 --> 25:42.976
John? John?
Iris?

25:43.019 --> 25:44.543
[ Door closes ]

25:44.586 --> 25:46.240
John?

25:49.112 --> 25:50.636
Oh, you're there.What is it?

25:50.679 --> 25:51.811
I'm back.

25:51.854 --> 25:53.769
M-Much earlier
than I thought.

25:53.813 --> 25:56.206
Yes, I came straight back.
I didn't know why I was there.

25:56.250 --> 25:57.860
You were going to do
an interview.

25:57.904 --> 25:59.514
What interview?I don't know.

25:59.558 --> 26:00.515
So, um...

26:00.559 --> 26:01.734
And see your publisher?

26:01.777 --> 26:02.909
Was it your publisher?

26:02.952 --> 26:06.173
So I came back.

26:06.216 --> 26:07.609
I didn't expect you back
for ages.

26:07.653 --> 26:09.916
Has she rung?I didn't answer.

26:09.959 --> 26:10.960
It was Nora!

26:11.004 --> 26:13.615
Iris, Nora's dead.

26:13.659 --> 26:16.966
Oh, so she is.
Oh, that is sad.

26:17.010 --> 26:18.402
Oh, well, never mind.

26:18.446 --> 26:20.230
Must have been Ed.

26:20.274 --> 26:24.495
What for?
Oh, yes, my book.

26:24.539 --> 26:27.498
Oh, so I came back.

26:29.500 --> 26:31.328
Man: What is, uh...

26:31.372 --> 26:34.897
the name
of the Prime Minister?

26:40.381 --> 26:42.122
Oh, me? Are you asking me?

26:42.165 --> 26:44.341
Yes, I am.

26:44.385 --> 26:46.343
I know.

26:46.387 --> 26:49.956
Okay, what is the name
of the Prime Minister?

26:49.999 --> 26:52.872
I don't know. Ask John.
Surely it doesn't matter.

26:52.915 --> 26:54.656
Okay, well,
no, not really.

26:54.700 --> 26:56.397
Someone will know.
[ Laughs ]

26:56.440 --> 26:57.659
[ Laughter ]

27:02.272 --> 27:04.840
Who would you like
to see?

27:04.884 --> 27:06.712
I mean,
is there anyone --

27:06.755 --> 27:08.365
I don't know.

27:08.409 --> 27:10.367
Shall I look up some names?
Talk to someone?

27:10.411 --> 27:12.718
I've got a lot of ideas,
but they won't come together.

27:12.761 --> 27:14.763
It happens all the time --
forgetting names.

27:14.807 --> 27:18.898
So, does it happen
all the time?

27:18.941 --> 27:22.075
I mean, you know, does
she mean writer's block?
I suppose she does, but...

27:22.118 --> 27:24.381
John:
Iris can always write,
doctor. This is --

27:24.425 --> 27:25.992
Oh, I know. Iris is a person --

27:26.035 --> 27:28.298
Yes, yes, but
it doesn't work like --

27:28.342 --> 27:30.300
Surely in
her case -- A-A woman
with a f-first-class mind.

27:30.344 --> 27:31.954
We will
have to be certain.

27:31.998 --> 27:36.524
There'll have to be
tests, scans.

27:36.567 --> 27:40.702
I don't think I can --
I mean, it's a little
beyond my competence.

27:40.746 --> 27:43.705
Iris finds her new book
v-very tiring and difficult.

27:43.749 --> 27:45.576
Basically, I'll
arrange something.

27:45.620 --> 27:47.535
Iris has
a very clear mind.

27:47.578 --> 27:49.711
Mine's a muddle,
but not hers.

27:49.755 --> 27:52.888
She does everything --
always has.

27:52.932 --> 27:54.890
Food, shopping,
tickets for things.

27:54.934 --> 27:58.502
I-I never know
how she m-m-manages

27:58.546 --> 28:00.591
and does her b-books
as well.

28:00.635 --> 28:03.029
Well, they can
get you help.

28:03.072 --> 28:06.641
N-No, no, no, no,
n-nobody would suit.

28:06.685 --> 28:08.948
There's
a very good place --

28:08.991 --> 28:10.906
a specialist nursing home --
Vale House.

28:10.950 --> 28:12.299
Not necessary.
Not yet.

28:12.342 --> 28:13.735
I'm sorry. N-N-Not your fault.

28:13.779 --> 28:15.084
Well, uh...take care.

28:15.128 --> 28:16.259
Goodbye, doctor.
Thank you.

28:16.303 --> 28:20.655
[ Bells rattle ]Goodbye.

28:22.439 --> 28:24.180
Iris?

28:24.224 --> 28:27.314
I'm sure the country
won't go to the dogs.

28:27.357 --> 28:29.490
Not knowing the Prime Minister's
name's not a capital offence.

28:29.533 --> 28:30.709
Absolutely.

28:30.752 --> 28:32.101
I know the names
that matter.

28:32.145 --> 28:33.929
It'll be all right.

28:33.973 --> 28:35.278
Well, it will be
if you stop worrying.

28:35.322 --> 28:37.585
I've got a book
to finish.

28:37.628 --> 28:42.242
Oh, Tony Blair --
so there.

28:49.640 --> 28:53.732
Iris, are you comfortable?
I'm going to start
the scan now.

28:53.775 --> 28:56.952
Just keep
nice and still.
Try to relax.

28:56.996 --> 28:58.824
It'll take
about 15 minutes.

29:27.896 --> 29:28.854
John.

29:28.897 --> 29:30.507
I'm very sorry.

29:30.551 --> 29:32.379
Is Iris still --
I'm so sorry I'm late.

29:32.422 --> 29:34.468
I don't know what's
going to happen, Janet.

29:34.511 --> 29:37.993
I've left the car outside.
The engine's running.

29:38.037 --> 29:39.821
Won't be a mo.
Right.

29:39.865 --> 29:41.257
See you out there.
Yes.

29:58.274 --> 29:59.841
John, I'm frightened.

29:59.885 --> 30:01.800
Everyone's doing
their best.

30:05.194 --> 30:07.414
Janet's got the car.

30:09.024 --> 30:11.200
It'll be...

30:19.861 --> 30:21.863
It's done.
You're finished?

30:21.907 --> 30:23.865
I thought
you were c-close.

30:23.909 --> 30:26.694
So far, but it hasn't made
any difference.

30:26.737 --> 30:29.566
Here's to it.

30:31.394 --> 30:32.395
Just try
and keep working.

30:32.439 --> 30:33.875
You must.
I will.

30:33.919 --> 30:35.616
And here's
to the next one.

30:35.659 --> 30:38.967
Just keep working,
keep talking,
keep the words coming.

30:39.011 --> 30:41.230
K-Keep at it.

30:41.274 --> 30:43.363
I shall come more like
a deprived animal

30:43.406 --> 30:45.321
if I can't write --
be like a starved dog.

30:45.365 --> 30:48.542
No. Keep at it.
I'll keep you at it.

30:48.585 --> 30:50.196
I feel...

30:50.239 --> 30:54.243
as if I'm sailing
into darkness.

30:59.422 --> 31:02.034
[ Beep ]

31:02.077 --> 31:05.472
A...sinuituis.

31:05.515 --> 31:06.473
[ Beep ]

31:06.516 --> 31:10.607
An...i...mal.

31:11.782 --> 31:13.132
[ Beep ]

31:13.175 --> 31:14.350
Toothbrush.

31:14.394 --> 31:20.139
Uh... Uh, no. Yes.

31:22.706 --> 31:24.447
[ Beep ]

31:24.491 --> 31:27.494
Por--

31:27.537 --> 31:30.627
P-- no.

31:30.671 --> 31:32.107
[ Beep ]

31:32.151 --> 31:35.458
Tennis thing.

31:35.502 --> 31:38.635
[ Beep ]

31:38.679 --> 31:41.682
God.

31:41.725 --> 31:44.728
Iris is getting t-tired,
I'm afraid.

31:44.772 --> 31:45.729
John.

31:45.773 --> 31:46.905
Can we have the blinds?

31:46.948 --> 31:48.776
Dame Iris,
thank you very much.

31:48.819 --> 31:49.777
Thank you.

31:49.820 --> 31:51.300
Well done, puss.

31:51.344 --> 31:52.954
Dame Iris,
thank you very much indeed.

31:52.998 --> 31:54.782
It was so kind of you
to come, Dame Iris.

31:54.825 --> 31:56.262
Thank you. I like it.
Thank you very much.

31:56.305 --> 31:57.263
Is it any help?

31:57.306 --> 32:01.441
What, to us?
Yes.

32:01.484 --> 32:03.704
It's...implacable.

32:03.747 --> 32:06.533
What does that mean?

32:06.576 --> 32:08.056
It means inexorable.

32:08.100 --> 32:10.276
I know
what the word means --

32:10.319 --> 32:13.496
um, to me -- to us.

32:13.540 --> 32:16.760
You see, words have meant
everything to her.

32:16.804 --> 32:20.199
They will still mean
something -- some thought.

32:20.242 --> 32:23.724
It can't just be
dead b-birds dropping.

32:23.767 --> 32:26.335
I know what it means,
and it doesn't surprise me.

32:26.379 --> 32:27.989
It frightens me, but --

32:28.033 --> 32:30.557
And then sometimes,
it doesn't frighten me,

32:30.600 --> 32:31.993
and that's just as bad,

32:32.037 --> 32:34.300
because that's it winning,
isn't it?

32:34.343 --> 32:38.434
N-N-No, no.
No, it's n-not.

32:38.478 --> 32:42.047
It won't win.

32:42.090 --> 32:44.832
It willwin.

32:44.875 --> 32:47.530
There.
It will win.

32:47.574 --> 32:50.490
That's very kind.

32:53.884 --> 32:57.062
Young Iris: Whoo!

32:57.105 --> 32:59.890
Young John: Iris!

32:59.934 --> 33:01.805
Iris, wait for me!

33:01.849 --> 33:05.635
Just keep tight hold of me,
and it'll be all right!

33:05.679 --> 33:07.463
You won't keep still!

33:07.507 --> 33:08.812
I can'tkeep still!

33:08.856 --> 33:10.597
I can't catch up
with you!

33:10.640 --> 33:12.425
Speed up!

33:12.468 --> 33:13.426
[ Laughing ] Oh!

33:13.469 --> 33:14.601
[ Laughing ] Whoo!

33:14.644 --> 33:16.995
[ Thunder rumbles ]

33:27.005 --> 33:28.441
Oh, good morning.

33:28.484 --> 33:32.749
Oh. No.
Uh...I...

33:32.793 --> 33:34.186
I think it's the...

33:34.229 --> 33:37.058
person who brings
the posts, John.

33:37.102 --> 33:38.581
Yes, it is.
Yes.

33:38.625 --> 33:39.887
John? So sorry.

33:39.930 --> 33:41.845
Thank you
very much indeed.

33:41.889 --> 33:42.933
Thank you.

33:42.977 --> 33:46.285
So sorry.

33:48.504 --> 33:51.420
There. There.

33:51.464 --> 33:54.162
Go on. Go on, go on,
go on, go on, go on.

33:56.121 --> 33:58.340
It's only the postman.

33:58.384 --> 33:59.602
It's only the postman.

33:59.646 --> 34:01.256
Don't repeat everything,
puss.

34:01.300 --> 34:02.953
It's only the postman.

34:02.997 --> 34:04.781
It's for you!
It's your book!

34:04.825 --> 34:06.000
What's that?

34:06.044 --> 34:07.001
Your book!

34:07.045 --> 34:09.090
It's only the postman.

34:09.134 --> 34:13.312
It's your book!

34:13.355 --> 34:16.010
Isn't it
perfectly splendid?

34:16.054 --> 34:18.752
Well, why don't you
look at it?

34:18.795 --> 34:22.190
It's only the postman.

34:30.719 --> 34:32.505
[ Cup shatters ]Damn.

34:32.547 --> 34:36.422
Stop nudging up to me
like a water buffalo.

34:36.465 --> 34:41.382
I have a lot to do.
Lots to do, Iris.

34:41.427 --> 34:43.210
See what I've done now?

34:43.255 --> 34:45.170
It's not your fault.
Not your fault.

34:45.213 --> 34:46.214
Sorry. Sorry.

34:46.257 --> 34:47.824
It's only the postman.

34:47.868 --> 34:49.348
Yes, all right!
It's only the postman!

34:49.391 --> 34:52.177
Sorry. So sorry.
There's lots to do.

35:14.416 --> 35:16.679
Which side do I go?

35:26.385 --> 35:28.561
[ Inhales, exhales deeply ]

35:31.607 --> 35:36.090
Prime Minister Blair:
Ask me my three main priorities
for government,

35:36.134 --> 35:39.354
and I tell you -- Education,
education, and education.

35:39.398 --> 35:40.834
[ Applause ]

35:40.877 --> 35:44.011
John! John! Why does
he keep saying that?

35:44.054 --> 35:47.667
What does he mean?
By what?

35:47.710 --> 35:50.800
"Education, education,
education."

35:52.280 --> 35:54.282
H-He means learning.

35:54.326 --> 35:56.415
Everyone g-getting
enough of it.

35:56.458 --> 35:58.199
Why does he
keep saying it?

35:58.243 --> 36:00.332
Politicians have to
keep repeating things

36:00.375 --> 36:01.681
to make themselves heard.

36:01.724 --> 36:03.204
They have to be
like travelers

36:03.248 --> 36:05.989
eating sheep's eyes
with B-Bedouins.

36:06.033 --> 36:10.603
They have to do anything
to make themselves liked.

36:10.646 --> 36:14.215
Why does he want to eat
a sheep's ear?

36:14.259 --> 36:16.348
Shall I turn it off?
No.

36:16.391 --> 36:19.829
We could go for a swim tomorrow
if it's n-not raining.

36:19.873 --> 36:21.788
No.
Yes. You love water.

36:21.831 --> 36:23.790
When you swim,
you love it.

36:23.833 --> 36:28.229
Swim --
swim is good for you.

36:28.273 --> 36:31.841
When are we leaving?

36:31.885 --> 36:33.713
Not today.

36:33.756 --> 36:35.584
Are we going to London?

36:35.628 --> 36:38.021
No, we're going
for a swim.

36:38.065 --> 36:41.721
When are we leaving?

36:41.764 --> 36:43.418
Not today.

36:45.812 --> 36:47.596
When are we leaving?

36:57.519 --> 37:01.654
Iris...
Iris, wait for me.

37:11.446 --> 37:14.623
Man:
You dirty old man.

37:14.667 --> 37:15.624
Hello!

37:15.668 --> 37:17.017
[ Laughs ]

37:17.060 --> 37:18.714
There we go.

37:18.758 --> 37:20.673
No, Iris,
not with your socks on.

37:20.716 --> 37:21.891
Your socks!

37:39.735 --> 37:42.825
[ Laughing ]

37:42.869 --> 37:43.870
Whoa!

37:49.571 --> 37:54.489
[ Laughter ]

37:54.533 --> 37:57.405
Look. Look. Look.

37:57.449 --> 37:58.928
[ Boys giggle ]

37:58.972 --> 38:01.409
Come along. Come on, come on,
come along.

38:01.453 --> 38:02.758
Go on.

38:09.025 --> 38:09.983
Ooh.

38:11.289 --> 38:14.117
[ Laughing ]

38:20.689 --> 38:22.212
Oh.

38:25.390 --> 38:28.218
[ Laughing ] Oh, yeah?

38:28.262 --> 38:29.611
[ Laughing ]

38:29.655 --> 38:31.874
Ah!

38:40.143 --> 38:41.754
Give me your hand.
Give me your hand.

38:41.797 --> 38:43.408
That's it. Give me your hand.
Give me your hand.

38:43.451 --> 38:46.149
No, no, don't --
Don't pull me in!

38:46.193 --> 38:48.151
You're all right.
I won't let you go.

38:48.195 --> 38:50.066
[ Gasping ]

38:50.110 --> 38:55.637
Let's get you dry.
You're all right.

38:55.681 --> 39:00.033
Come on. Here.
Up your hands.

39:00.076 --> 39:01.904
Up your hands.
Let's get you warm.

39:01.948 --> 39:05.168
That's it. That's it.
Come on. That's it.

39:05.212 --> 39:07.780
No, Iris. Iris!
Just put your --
Like this, up high. Up.

39:07.823 --> 39:11.305
Let's get your head
through.
Let's go now.

39:11.349 --> 39:13.394
As soon as you got
your head in.
Let's go now!

39:13.438 --> 39:15.875
Iris, as soon as we've
got your head in!
No. No.

39:15.918 --> 39:18.007
Iris! As soon as
we've got -- Come on.

39:18.051 --> 39:20.662
Young Iris:
Where's my petticoat?

39:20.706 --> 39:22.882
Here.
Ah.

39:26.364 --> 39:27.756
[ Clears throat ]

39:27.800 --> 39:30.106
Are you sure
he's expecting me?

39:35.547 --> 39:38.071
[ Bell rings ]

39:44.643 --> 39:46.427
Maurice.

39:46.471 --> 39:48.560
I brought John.
You said I might.

39:48.603 --> 39:50.779
Did I? And did
you say you would?

39:50.823 --> 39:53.565
Yes.
Well, come in.

39:53.608 --> 39:57.351
Maurice Charlton.J-John Bayley.

40:03.531 --> 40:04.967
Isn't it hot?

40:05.011 --> 40:06.404
Yes, it is.

40:06.447 --> 40:08.797
I've got just the thing
will cool.

40:12.845 --> 40:15.413
[ Whispering ] I imagine
your friend Maurice

40:15.456 --> 40:17.371
is hoping to have
his wicked will, is he?

40:17.415 --> 40:18.981
[ Whispering ]
Not today is he.

40:27.686 --> 40:31.429
You and I are much the same age,
aren't we, John?

40:31.472 --> 40:32.604
Yeah, I-I think so.

40:32.647 --> 40:33.953
Does it matter?

40:33.996 --> 40:35.563
No.

40:35.607 --> 40:37.957
This is not important,
i-is it?

40:38.000 --> 40:41.830
What Maurice means
is that most of my real --

40:41.874 --> 40:44.877
my otherfriends
are older than me.

40:44.920 --> 40:47.357
Much older.

40:47.401 --> 40:49.272
Yes, and there's
a very good reason for that,

40:49.316 --> 40:50.273
isn't there?

40:50.317 --> 40:51.710
Is there? What?

40:51.753 --> 40:53.668
She likes people
with a bit of a past.

40:53.712 --> 40:55.365
She uses them --
don't you?

40:55.409 --> 40:56.715
No, I don't.

40:56.758 --> 40:58.151
For your novel.
Don't you, Iris?

40:58.194 --> 41:01.981
I-I haven't read it.Haven't you?

41:02.024 --> 41:04.766
Neither have you, Maurice,
so don't play games.

41:04.810 --> 41:07.465
Nobody has read it.[ Cork pops ]

41:07.508 --> 41:12.034
The gentle lady hasn't yet
bestowed her favor on anyone.

41:12.078 --> 41:16.299
I-Iris doesn't like
to talk about it.
I know that, too, Iris.

41:16.343 --> 41:18.432
That's because it's full
of people she knows --

41:18.476 --> 41:21.522
All these masters of thought
you're so chummy with.

41:21.566 --> 41:23.437
Bound to be.
We all know.

41:23.481 --> 41:25.047
Isn't it, Iris?

41:25.091 --> 41:27.397
No, it isn't, but you can
think what you like.

41:27.441 --> 41:29.530
You know nothing about it.
Nobody knows but me.

41:29.574 --> 41:30.966
And...I'm not telling.

41:31.010 --> 41:32.925
I thought
it was a secret.

41:32.968 --> 41:37.625
I mean, I know Iris
doesn't want it talked about.

41:37.669 --> 41:39.192
Come on, Iris.

41:39.235 --> 41:40.846
I'm sure we'll all
recognize ourselves.

41:40.889 --> 41:42.325
I don't see how you --
anyone -- can.

41:42.369 --> 41:46.765
They won't.
T-T-They won't.

41:46.808 --> 41:48.984
I hate that sort of thing.
I won't ever do it.

41:49.028 --> 41:50.508
I don't see the point of
writing a novel that's
autobiography.

41:50.551 --> 41:52.118
There's no fun in that.

41:52.161 --> 41:53.554
T-They won't see
themselves, you know?

41:53.598 --> 41:54.773
D-Don't people
w-written about in novels

41:54.816 --> 41:55.991
always s-see themselves
differently?

41:56.035 --> 41:57.819
I'm sure they do.

